---
title: "Error Handling without Exceptions"
author: bad-antics
date: 2026-04-06
abstract: Lateralus treats errors as structured data using Result types and error codes E1001-E7004, providing a safer alternative to exceptions for systems code.
---

## What are Exceptions?

Exceptions are often used in programming to handle runtime errors. However, they have limitations. They can lead to "try-except"-blocks that clutter the codebase and make debugging more difficult.

## The Problem with Exceptions

Exceptions are not suitable for all situations. They don't provide enough information about the error and can lead to lost context when propagating errors up the call stack.

## Structured Error Handling with Results

Lateralus provides a safer alternative: `Result` types and error codes. Instead of relying on exceptions, we use a combination of values to represent potential outcomes.

fn example(x: int) -> Result<int, Error> {
    if x < 0 {
        return Err(E1001); // Invalid input value
    }
    Ok(x * 2)
}

In this example, `example` returns either an integer (`Ok`) or an error code (`Err`).

## Error Codes

Lateralus uses a standardized set of error codes (E1001-E7004). These codes provide a clear way to communicate errors without relying on exception handling.

| Error Code | Description |
| --- | --- |
| E1001 | Invalid input value |
| E2001 | Resource unavailable |
| E3001 | Unexpected behavior |

We can propagate these error codes through our code using `Result`.

fn divide(a: float, b: float) -> Result<float, Error> {
    match b {
        0.0 => Err(E2001), // Division by zero
        _ => {
            let result = a / b;
            Ok(result)
        }
    }
}

fn main() {
    let result = divide(10.0, 0.0);
    match result {
        Ok(value) => println!("{} divided by {} is {}", 10.0, 0.0, value),
        Err(err_code) => println!("Error {}: {}", err_code, ErrDescription(err_code)),
    }
}

// Helper function to get the human-readable description of an error code
fn ErrDescription(err_code: u16) -> String {
    match err_code {
        E1001 => "Invalid input value".to_string(),
        E2001 => "Division by zero".to_string(),
        _ => "Unknown error".to_string(),
    }
}

In this example, we use `match` to handle different cases in the `divide` function and return either a successful result (`Ok`) or an error code (`Err`). We then propagate the error code up the call stack using `match` again.

